Bifunctional catalysts for oxygen reduction reaction and oxygen evolution reaction in Zinc-air batteries have been long pursued for the development of clean energy transformation devices. Yet, the underlying mechanism of the promoted electrocatalytic performance is still vague. Herein, a pyrolysis-free Co/Fe bimetallic phthalocyanine coordination polymer Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is firstly synthesized using heterometal tetra-aminophthalocyanines (MTAPcs, M=Co/Fe) as structural model and N,N,N’,N’-tetra(4-folmylphenyl)-p-phenylenediamine (TPDA) as linker. The Co/Fe-TPDA-CP exhibits the high oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) and oxygen evolution reaction (OER) activities with low ΔE of 692 mV, superior to monometallic Fe-TPDA-CP and Co-TPDA-CP polymers. Density functional theory (DFT) calculation and thermodynamic analysis find that ORR and OER happened separately on Fe and Co sites, in which the presence of second metal modulates the d-band center and optimizes the intermediates adsorption, thereby improving the ORR/OER synergistically. Moreover, dynamic analysis explains that the enhanced ORR stability originated from the fast H2O2 decomposition catalyzed by Co-N4 sites. Furthermore, the Zn-air battery with Co/Fe-TPDA-CP electrode also exhibits a high peak power density (97 mW cm−2) and specific capacity (780 mA h g −1). Through the proof-of-concept bifunctional electrocatalyst with clear structure and synergistic mechanism, this work paves the way for future molecular oxygen electrocatalyst design. Keywords Bimetallic electrocatalysts ORR/OER Thermodynamic and kinetic study Synergistic effect Phthalocyanine polymer Data availability Data will be made available on request. 1 Introduction Zinc-air batteries (ZABs), as an emerging electrochemical storage device with high energy density and low manufacturing cost, has great potentials in various electrical devices like electric vehicles (EVs) and smartphones [1–3]. However, sluggish kinetics of cathodic oxygen evolution reaction (OER) and oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) during charging and discharging process has hindered the application of ZABs due to lack of efficient electrocatalysts [4]. To overcome the limitation above, noble metal (Pt, Ir, Ru) based electrocatalysts have been developed and commercialized as the benchmark of electrocatalytic performance [5,6]. Yet, the high cost and poor bifunctional performance have encouraged researchers to turn to non-noble metal oxygen electrocatalysts [7–9]. To lower the metal usage and increase the atomic economy of active sties, an intuitive strategy is reducing sizes of catalytic species into molecular/atomic level, so called single-atom catalyst (SACs) [10,11]. Especially iron based Fe-N-C catalysts, showing a boosted catalytic activity due to the high atom utilization efficiency and customized coordination environment, are viewed as promising catalysts of ZABs [12,13]. However, the monotonous nature of single active site leads to linear relationship between the adsorption energy of oxygen-containing intermediates and catalytic activity, making it hard to break the scaling relation [14,15]. Moreover, Fe-N4 usually suffers from low stability due to the accumulation of H2O2 produced through 2 electron oxygen reduction or Fenton reaction [16,17]. In this regard, some research focus on creating Fe/M heterometallic catalysts to modulate the d-band structure of metals through synergistic interactions, and improves the ORR activity and stability of the catalysts [18–21]. Metal tetrapyrrole compounds such as metal porphyrins (MPors) and metal phthalocyanines (MPcs), with layirge π-conjugated structure and enzymatic M-N4 center, are viewed as desirable catalyst model to build Fe/M heterometallic catalysts [22–25]. Mai's group reported a mixture of FePc and CoPc, which displayed a better ORR performance with robust kinetic current density (enhanced by >100 %) and stability (increased by 20.5 %). Through DFT calculation, they found that the increased interaction between CoPc and FePc modulates the bond length of Fe-N and the electron density around the Fe-N4, somewhat reducing the hydrogen peroxide yield [26]. Yet, current bimetallic phthalocyanine based electrocatalysts are short in direct experimental evidence of the synergistic effect on the enhanced activity and stability. The diarylamine derived ligands, exhibiting redox active center and p-type electronic nature, are desirable building blocks for electrochemical devices and electrocatalysts [27]. Herein, we have constructed a bifunctional catalyst Co/Fe-TPDA-CP for ORR/OER through integrating cobalt tetra-aminophthalocyanine (CoTAPc) and iron tetra-aminophthalocyanine (FeTAPc) with diarylamine-based ligand, N,N,N’,N’-tetra(4-folmylphenyl)-p-phenylenediamine (TPDA). The bimetallic Co/Fe coordination polymer has shown the optimized activity, with the half-wave potential of 0.88 V for ORR and the overpotential of 340 mV for OER. More importantly, through combining experimental and theoretical data, origin of the activity was tested. The excellent ORR stability is demonstrated by Damjanovic model simulation and dynamical analysis, where reaction rate on consecutive 2e− reduction is vital to consume accumulated H2O2. 2 Experimental section 2.1 Synthesis of catalysts The synthesis of building blocks (MTAPcs, M=Co/Fe) and linker (TPDA) are detailed in the Supporting Information. The monometallic Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP are firstly prepared through Schiff base reaction for the comparative purpose. Typically, Cobalt tetra-aminophthalocyanine (CoTAPc), Iron tetra-aminophthalocyanine (FeTAPc) were used as the basic building units and equal molar of N,N,N’,N’-tetra(4-folmylphenyl)-p-phenylenediamine (TPDA) was introduced as linkers. And then the bimetallic Co/Fe-TPDA-CP was synthesized with equal Fe and Co contents by adding the same stoichiometric CoTAPc and FeTAPc molecules reacted with TPDA, as detailed in the Fig. 1 a. Co-TPDA-CP: An DMAc (4.0 mL) solution of CoTAPc (126.3 mg, 0.2 mmol) and TPDA (105.1 mg, 0.2 mmol) was degassed in a Pyrex tube (10 mL) by three freeze-pump-thaw cycles. The tube was sealed off and heated at 150 °C for 72 h. After cooling to room temperature, the precipitate was collected by centrifugation, washed with THF, chloroform, and acetone for several times, extracted by Soxhlet with THF for 24 h, and dried at 120 °C under vacuum overnight to give the product as dark green powder in 72.1 % isolated yield. Fe-TPDA-CP: The Fe-TPDA-CP were prepared by using stoichiometric amounts of FeTAPc, in place of CoTAPc in the above procedure (Yield: 72.3 %). Co/Fe-TPDA-CP: The Co/Fe-TPDA-CP were prepared by using CoTAPc (63.2 mg, 0.1 mmol) and FeTAPc (62.8 mg, 0.1 mmol) in place of CoTAPc in the above procedure (Yield: 71.9 %). 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Structural characterizations Fourier transform infrared spectra (FT-IR) confirm the successful fabrication of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP from monomers. As showed in Fig. 1b, obtained polymers contained the characteristic peaks at ∼740, ∼1080, ∼1120, ∼1350 cm−1 referring to the macrocyclic structure of phthalocyanine [28,29]. The Co-N and Fe-N stretching vibration still exist in range from 748 to 753 cm−1 in the polymers, similar to that of the metal aminophthalocyanine monomers (MTAPcs, M=Co/Fe). In particular, the M-N peak of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is situated at 750 cm−1, between that of Co-TPDA-CP(748 cm−1) and Fe-TPDA-CP(753 cm−1), suggesting that there is a certain electron transfer between the metals in the bimetallic catalyst compared with monometallic system [30]. Besides, the sharp peak at 1690 cm−1 confirms the successful formation of imine bonds (C = N), while peaks located at ∼1700 cm−1 for C = O vibration band of N,N,N’,N’-tetra(4-folmylphenyl)-p-phenylenediamine (TPDA) and 3400–3200, 1600 cm−1 for NH vibration bands of metal tetra-aminophthalocyanines (MTAPc) diminished [27,31]. Similar results were found in Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP. The powder X-ray diffraction (XRD) results of Co-TPDA-CP, Fe-TPDA-CP and Co/Fe-TPDA-CP displayed wide polymeric peaks at about 7.2∼8.5° and 24.3∼25.5° (Figure S1), corresponding to d-spacing of 1.10∼1.26 and 0.33∼0.36 nm [32], respectively, which are close to the accumulated phthalocyanine momomers [33,34]. Therefore, these diffraction results could be assigned to the stacking distances between tetrapyrrole cores of neighbouring metal phthalocyanine molecules along the directions in parallel and perpendicular to the tetrapyrrole rings. It can be concluded that the packing modes of metal phthalocyanine conjugated polymers are very similar regardless of metal ions. In addition, the 13C solid-state nuclear magnetic resonance (CP-MAS) measurements of N,N,N’,N’-tetra(4-folmylphenyl)-p-phenylenediamine (TPDA), metal-free tetra-aminophthalocyanine (TAPc) and metal-free phthalocyanine conjugated polymer (metalfree-TPDA-CP) were synthetized to analyse the chemical composition. As showed in Fig. 1c, the peaks at ∼130, ∼148 and ∼151 ppm were assigned to the carbons on the amino phthalocyanine macrocycle and benzene of TPDA, which are similar to present in the TAPc and TPDA [28], Figure S2. It is worth noting that a new characteristic signal (C=N) in metalfree-TPDA-CP was found at 169 ppm ascribing to the carbonyl C-atoms of the imine group, further confirming the formation of the imine linkage [35]. And the peak at 190 ppm was attributed to the unpolymerized aldehyde carbon at the edge of metalfree-TPDA-CP. In addition, metalfree-TPDA-CP exhibited wider bands in the range of 100–150 ppm than the TAPc, which could be designated to the low crystallinity of those polymers, as validated from the XRD. As well, the solid-state UV–vis diffuse reflectance spectra of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP in Fig. 1d showed the characteristic Q-band of metal phthalocyanine at 648, 623 and 654 nm. This demonstrates that the introduction of TPDA has not altered the conjugated macrocyclic structure of the metal-amino phthalocyanine. However, distinctive blue-shift of the Q-bands was observed for the polymers in compare with molecular FeTAPc (703 nm) and CoTAPc (682 nm) in DMF. (Figure S3), indicated face-to-face packing mode of the MTAPc (M=Fe and Co) in the polymers. The field-emission scanning electron microscopy (FE-SEM) images showed the morphology of polymers with the lamellar stacking shapes of bimetallic Co/Fe-TPDA-CP (Figure S4 a), inherited from its two-dimensional (2D) polymer structure. Stacked 2D nanosheets have also present in mono-metallic Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP, Figure S4 b and c. Obviously, the types and amounts of the central metal did not significantly affect the morphology of the polymers, consistent with the results of XRD analysis. Then, the elemental mapping images was observed by energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy analysis, suggesting that the C, N, Fe, and Co were evenly dispersed in Figure S5. TEM measurement also has been carried out for Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, as shown in Figure S6, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP were stacked by smaller size nanosheets, consistent with SEM results. The BET results are shown in Figure S7, showing that the specific surface area of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is 12.63 m2/g. This is due to the disordered stacking pattern of the polymer resulting in its pores being frequently occupied [28]. 3.2 Electrochemical catalytic performances Based on the above results and analysis, the electrocatalytic activity of three conjugated polymers were evaluated by the three-electrode system in alkaline conditions. The cyclic voltammetry (CV) curves in 0.1 M KOH under saturated O2 condition were displayed in Figure S8. It could be found that three catalysts exhibit apparent peaks in saturated O2 condition, indicating that the obtained catalysts have ORR activity. In addition, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP with bimetallic sites displayed the most positive reduction peak potential at 0.88 V than that of Fe-TPDA-CP (0.87 V) and Co-TPDA-CP (0.80 V) with single metallic sites in O2-saturated. The liner sweep voltammetry (LSV) further confirms the higher ORR electrocatalytic activity of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP. As shown in Fig. 2 a, the most positive onset potential (Eonset) of 0.98 V, half-wave (E1/2) of 0.88 V and the limiting current density (JL) of −6.23 mA cm−2 were verified in Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, superior than Fe-TPDA-CP (Eonset = 0.97 V, E1/ 2 = 0.87 V, JL= −6.15 mA cm−2), Co-TPDA-CP (Eonset = 0.91 V, E1/ 2 = 0.80 V, JL= −5.27 mA cm−2) and commercial 20 % Pt/C (Eonset = 0.97 V, E1/ 2 = 0.84 V, JL= −6.12 mA cm−2). In addition, Figure S9 a show that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP possesses the faster electron transfer rate with a smaller Tafel slope of 54.73 mV dec−1 than that of Fe-TPDA-CP (55.38 mV dec−1) and Co-TPDA-CP (72.61 mV dec−1). It indicated that the introduction of a second metal improves the reactivity and reaction kinetics of ORR [36]. Besides, the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP catalysts containing Fe-N4 sites have a higher activity than Co-TPDA-CP, implying Fe-N4 as the more appropriate ORR active site relative to Co-N4 sites in conjugated systems of polymers. LSV curves at various rotation speeds ranging from 400 to 2025 rpm has been tested to further understand the reaction pathway [37]. The fitted Koutecky-Levich (K-L) plots show remarkable linearity at every potential in Figure S10. This shows that the number of transferred electrons of each oxygen molecule in ORR is almost same. Electron transfer number (n) of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, Fe-TPDA-CP and Co-TPDA-CP catalysts were calculated to be 3.93, 3.89 and 3.84, separately, similar to electron transfer number n of 20 % Pt/C (n = 4.00). This indicated the four-electron reaction mechanism of three catalysts. The electron transfer number n was further estimated using a rotating ring disk electrode (RRDE) and the peroxide generation of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, Fe-TPDA-CP and Co-TPDA-CP also be monitored. As depicted in Fig. 2b, H2O2 yield of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP maintained 11.62 %, lower than that of Fe-TPDA-CP (27.31 %) and Co-TPDA-CP (15.42 %). The average electron transfer number of three catalysts were 3.91, 3.88 and 3.87 respectively, matching those of K-L plots. It is interesting to note that the above catalysts also exhibit prominent activity of oxygen evolution reaction (OER) in 1 M KOH. The over-potential (E10) of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is only 340 mV at the current intensity of 10 mA cm−2 in Fig. 2c, lower than commercial RuO2(E10 = 390 mV). Similarly, Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP also exhibit catalytic activity with 480 and 500 mV of E10. The Tafel slope of three catalysts (Figure S9 b) are displayed in the order of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP (90.83 mV dec−1) < Co-TPDA-CP (94.24 mV dec−1) < Fe-TPDA-CP (168.51 mV dec−1). The smaller Tafel slope further explains the excellent catalytic kinetics of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP. The above results indicate that the catalyst containing Co-N4 sites has better OER electrochemical activity than that of Fe-N4 sites. Nyquist plots of electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) reveal that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP has the minimum arc diameter, as showed as Figure S11, which well matched with Tafel slope results of ORR and OER. That means Co/Fe-TPDA-CP has the smallest mass transfer resistance and the highest charge transfer efficiency during electrochemical processes [38]. In other words, the synergy of the bimetallic centers enhanced the reaction kinetics and reduced the energy barrier of electron transport in the electrode-electrolyte interface. Therefore, the difference of OER and ORR metrics(ΔE = E 10 - E1/2) was used to estimate the entire oxygen electrode activity [39]. As shown in Fig. 2d and Table S1, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP display a ΔE of 692 mV, superior to Co-TPDA-CP (1258 mV) and Fe-TPDA-CP (1380 mV), indicating that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP with bimetallic sites has the highest ORR/OER bifunctional activity in the same environment. Furthermore, the cyclic voltammetry (CV) with different scan rates of the three catalysts from 80 mV s −1 to 180 mV s −1 has been tested to reflect the ratio of electrochemically active surface area (ECSA) to double-layer capacitance (Cdl), which can further reflect the electrochemical activity. As can be seen from Figure S12 and 13, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP has more exposed surface reaction sites with a higher Cdl value (8.57 mF cm−2) superior to Co-TPDA-CP (Cdl = 1.67 mF cm−2), Fe-TPDA-CP (Cdl = 2.09 mF cm−2). It is well known that the activity and stability of electrocatalysts are equally important in practical applications. I-t chronoamperometric response was used to investigate the ORR durability of catalysts in Figure S14, Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP with single metallic site retain 80.82 % and 74.23 % of their original current densities after 40,000 s operation without break, respectively. However, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP shows outstanding durability with 94.74 % of initial current due to the synergistic effect of bimetallic active sites in the equal period operation. Combined with the results of RRDE, speculating that the low stability of the Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP is due to the high production of H2O2 (with 15.42 % and 27.31 %) to irreversibly break the active site during the electrochemical processes, resulting in partial deactivation of the two catalysts. On the other hand, the polarization curve was carried out to evaluate the OER stability of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP. As showed in Figure S15, the LSV curve seldom shifted after 5000 CV cycles. This indicates the excellent OER stability of obtained catalyst. The morphology and structure of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP were also analyzed to further prove the stability of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP. Co/Fe-TPDA-CP mixed with equal mass of carbon black (Vulcan XC-72) shows the amorphous spheric structure inherited from carbon black (Figure S16 a, b). The negligible change for morphology was observed even after the 40,000 s i-t chronoamperometric response for ORR (Figure S16 c, d) and 5000 CV cycles for OER (Figure S16 e, f). Furthermore, the Fe 2p and Co 2p spectra of XPS were used to further monitor the structure and chemical state changes after a long time of ORR and OER stability test, respectively. As exhibited in Figure S17, The Fe 2p and Co 2p energy level spectra remain negligible change after ORR and OER cycles, suggesting remarkable stability of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP. 3.3 Mechanistic study 3.3.1 Valence-band structure and XPS study To begin with, UV–vis diffuse reflectance spectra (DRS) was used to evaluate the band gap. As displayed in Figure S18, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP exhibits smaller value of energy gap (Eg = 1.23 eV) than Fe-TPDA-CP (Eg = 1.32 eV) and Co-TPDA-CP (Eg = 1.30 eV). A small value of energy gap for Co/Fe-TPDA-CP demonstrated that the enhanced electron transfer ability for reaction [40]. Then the frontier molecular orbital of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, Fe-TPDA-CP and Co-TPDA-CP was studied by ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) and the possible mechanism of improved electrocatalytic performance of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP was identified. Fig. 3 reveals the disparate frontier molecular orbitals energy level of three catalysts, where Co/Fe-TPDA-CP shows the higher E HOMO of −4.99 eV and ELUMO = −3.76 V than that of Fe-TPDA-CP (E HOMO = −5.09 eV, ELUMO = −3.80 eV) and Co-TPDA-CP (E HOMO = −5.16 eV, ELUMO = −3.86 eV). According to the frontier molecular orbital theory, the transfer of partial d electrons from metal ions to the π* orbital of O2 can be accelerated by a higher HOMO level, which facilitates the adsorption and activation of O2 in the active-sites and thus renders Co/Fe-TPDA-CP excellent bifunctional oxygen electrocatalysts [41,42]. Additionally, work function (Ø) is calculated to evaluate the electron delocalization ability, which accelerates the electron transfer between the oxygen intermediates and active site [43]. As showed as Fig. 3c, the order of work function is Co/Fe-TPDA-CP (Ø = 3.85 eV) < Fe-TPDA-CP (Ø = 3.96 eV) < Co -TPDA-CP (Ø = 4.12 eV), indicating that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP possesses the lower electron transfer barrier and higher electron donation ability in the electrocatalysis process. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) further discloses the coordination environment and chemical states of three catalysts. The XPS survey spectra in Figure S19 reflect that the catalysts contain C, N, Co and Fe elements for Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, C, N and Co elements for Co-TPDA-CP and C, N and Fe elements for Fe-TPDA-CP, respectively. Specially, the content ratio of Co and Fe elements on the surface of the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst is about 1:1, which is consistent with the inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS) results (Table S2). The graphitic N (401.4∼402.2 eV), pyrrolic N (400.1∼400.3 eV), M-N (399.4∼399.7 eV) and pyridinic N (398.6∼398.8 eV) species can be observed in the high-resolution N 1 s spectra of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, Co-TPDA-CP and Fe-TPDA-CP (Fig. 4 a) [44,45] By comparing the contents of the four N species of the three CPs in Figure S20 and Table S3, finding that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP contains more graphitic N (29.98 %) and pyridinic N (32.82 %) species than those of Fe-TPDA-CP (15.43 % and 31.34 %) and Co-TPDA-CP (11.91 % and 21.90%). It is well known that graphitic N can deviate the electron distribution of carbon and boost the adsorption and desorption of oxygen-containing intermediates. Similarly, pyridinic N species provide more active sites, which also helps to improve the catalytic performances [46]. Meanwhile, the high-resolution Co 2p spectra of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP and Co-TPDA-CP can be deconvoluted into Co 2p3/2, Co 2p1/2 and satellite peaks, whereas Co 2p3/2 specie negatively shifts from 782.01 eV of Co -TPDA-CP to 780.79 eV of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP in Fig. 4b. In good contrast, the positive shift of Fe-TPDA-CP to Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is observed in the high-resolution Fe 2p spectra, where the peaks of Fe 2p3/2, Fe 2p1/2 and satellite peaks are assigned in Fig. 4c. The binding energy of Fe 2p3/2 shifted 0.76 eV in the positive direction (from 711.12 eV of Fe-TPDA-CP to 711.88 eV of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP) after the introduction of the second metal. The shift of binding energy indicates the diversion of electrons from Fe center to Co center in Co/Fe-TPDA-CP with bimetallic sites. Besides, the introduction of the second metal also alternates the coordination environment of all metal ions on the carbon skeleton. The C 1 s spectra of three catalysts appeared four deconvoluted peaks corresponding to C = C/CC (284.6∼284.7 eV), CN (285.7∼285.8 eV), C = N (287.5∼287.7 eV) and π →π* satellite peaks in Fig. 4d. The peak at 284.7 eV belongs to the π-band (1s→π*) transition, so the half-maximum full width (FWHM) of the C = C/CC bond peak can assess the number of delocalized π-electrons (DDE) quantitatively [47], in other words, the narrow FWHM reflects the higher electron delocalization in the carbon plane [48]. As showed in the Figure S21, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP appears the narrower FWHM of 1.11 compared to 1.22 of Co-TPDA-CP and 1.13 of Fe-TPDA-CP, indicating that there are more delocalized π-electrons in Co/Fe-TPDA-CP which favourable for electrochemical reactions. 3.3.2 Damjanovic model simulation dynamical analysis Electrochemical test results showed that the ORR process of the three polymers were all four-electron transfer, but their activity and stability were significantly different. In order to explore the mechanism of synergistic enhancement of activity and stability on Fe/Co bimetallic sites, kinetic analysis of the contribution of separated sites on ORR were performed. The classical Damjanovic model for the ORR (Figure S22) was used to extract the respective reaction rate constants (see details in supplemental information), including the direct four-electron reduction rate constant (k1), and two consecutive two-electron reduction pathways of O2 to H2O2 (k2) and H2O2 to H2O (k3) combining RRDE voltammetry [10,49] (Fig. 5 ). As depicted in Fig. 6 a, the Fe-N4 site has similar value of k1 and k2 in Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst, which rises simultaneously along with increase in voltage, indicating competing relationship between 4e and sequential 2e ORR [50]. On the contrary, k3 decreases with the increase in voltage, k3 value is almost 0 when the E = 0.8 V, which leads to a large amount of hydrogen peroxide accumulation at Fe-N4 site during ORR process, resulting in a decrease in its stability. Similarly, the Co-N4 site in the Co-TPDA-CP catalyst maintains almost the same value of k1, k2 and k3 at low potential (< 0.5 V), as exhibited in Fig. 6b. However, with the increase in voltage, k3 increased greatly and even exceeded k1, instantly transferring H2O2 to H2O at high potential and promoting the continuous 2 electron process. In other words, the less accumulation of hydrogen peroxide produced by consecutive 2e process enhances the ORR stability of Co-TPDA-CP. The above results are consistent with those of electrochemical activity and stability tests. As for Co/Fe-TPDA-CP, Fig. 6c appears that the catalyst exhibits high k1 over twice of k2, indicating a leading 4-electron process under the synergistic action of Fe-N4 and Co-N4 active sites in the 0.4∼0.8 V. It is interesting to note that k2 and k3 are almost equal at low voltage (<0.5 V). As the voltage increases, k2 decreases and k3 increases, like above mentioned Co-N4 site, which reduces the possibility of the catalyst deactivation to some certain extent. Therefore, the efficient 4-electron process combined with the low H2O2 accumulation endow the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst with high activity and stability. 3.3.3 Understanding ORR mechanism by DFT calculation To further reveal the dynamics of ORR and OER processes at different sites, theoretical simulation was applied through the first primitive calculation [51]. (The concrete methods were shown in Supporting Information). The adsorption of oxygen on the active site is the first step of the ORR process. So the adsorption energy of oxygen was calculated on the Co-N4 site in the Co-TPDA-CP catalyst, the Fe-N4 site in the Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst and both Fe-N4 and Co-N4 sites in the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst, separately [52]. Figure S23 and Table S4 showed that the adsorption energy of oxygen at the Fe-N4 site in the Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst (0.91 eV) was significantly higher than that of the Co-N4 site in the Co-TPDA-CP catalyst (0.60 eV), explaining the high activity of Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst over Co-TPDA-CP catalyst. Similarly, the oxygen adsorption energy of Fe-N4 site (Ead=0.90 eV) is greater than that of Co-N4 site (Ead=0.59 eV) in the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst. This is because the electron cloud density at the Fe center is much higher than that of Co (Table. S5), which is conducive to the coupling of electron-withdrawing oxygen. In summary, Fe-N4 is considered to be the main ORR active site, which is consistent with the outstanding electrochemical activity of polymers containing Fe-N4. Based on the above, the Gibbs free energy of all catalysts for ORR at different electrode potentials were calculated. Fig. 7 a shows that the change of free energy at all three sites is negative when U = 0 V, indicating that the ORR process is spontaneous in thermodynamics. At 1.23 V (Fig. 7b), the formation of *OOH from O2 in the Co-TPDA-CP catalyst crosses the highest energy barrier of 0.645 eV because of the low O2 adsorption energy of Co-N4. However, as the oxygen adsorption energy increases, *OOH formation becomes downhill, while the fourth step *OH resolution becomes the rate determining step (RDS) of the ORR process in the Fe-N4 site of Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst and Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst. Notably, the Gibbs free energy change for RDS on the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst is 0.483 eV, which is lower than that for the Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst (0.558 eV). This can be attributed to the downshifts of the d-band center from −3.867 eV of Fe-TPDA-CP to −3.985 eV of the bimetallic polymer Co/Fe-TPDA-CP in Fig. 7c. According to the theory of d-band center, the decreased d-band center weakens the adsorption of Fe-N4 with *OH, which is instrumental in the desorption of *OH [53]. In other words, the introduction of the second metal further optimized the RDS of the ORR process. On the basis of the results obtained by the classical Damjanovic model, the change of free energy of decomposition of H2O2 was calculated to investigate the role of Co-N4 of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst in the ORR process. Figure S24 shows that the adsorption of *H2O2 at Fe-N4 site is energetically unfavored, indicating that the reaction is difficult to occur at this site when U = 0 V. On the contrary, the whole process of H2O2 reduction at Co-N4 site is thermodynamically favorable, which proves that the Fe-N4 is more favorable to the direct 4-electron reduction process, while the Co-N4 can accelerate the continuous 2-electron process and reduces the production of H2O2. The results of DFT calculation are in line with the Damjanovic model simulation. Therefore, under the synergistic action of the two sites, the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst promoted the ORR process with a higher driving force and obtained a lower hydrogen peroxide yield with 11.62 %, resulting in high activity and stability. In addition, for OER process, free energy change of the Co-N4 site in the Co-TPDA-CP catalyst, the Fe-N4 site in the Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst, the Co-N4 site in the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst are also calculated. As displayed in Fig. 7a, the changes of free energy at all three sites are all uphill and the calculated overpotential is similar to the results of electrochemical tests when the U = 0 V in Table S6. The calculated overpotential is similar to the results of electrochemical test. However, when U = 1.23 V, significant difference are revealed between the Co-N4 site and the Fe-N4 site in the trend of free energy change (Fig. 7d). Notably, the RDS of the Fe-N4 site is *O → *OOH, while the Co-N4 site is limited by the *OH → *O step. Specifically, the change of Gibbs free energy for the RDS on the Co-N4 site in the Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is 0.341 eV, lower than those of the Co-N4 site in the Co-TPDA-CP (0.477 eV) and the Fe-N4 site in the Fe-TPDA-CP (0.626 eV). In addition, the rise of the d-band center level (Ed) of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP (Ed = −3.985 eV) relative to Co-TPDA-CP (Ed = −4.067 eV) indicates the rise of anti-bonding energy state in the d-band center theory. This can enhance the interaction between the intermediate adsorbent and Co-N4, which is conducive to enhancing the adsorption capacity of the intermediate products in OER process [54,55]. Therefore, it can be seen that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst possesses a lower energy barrier to promotes the reaction, resulting in a significant OER performance. 3.4 Application in Zn-air battery In view of the prominent ORR and OER performances in alkaline conditions, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP was used as the air cathode electrocatalyst (the mass loading was 1.0 mg cm−2) in a rechargeable Zn-air battery with 6 M KOH containing 0.2 M Zn(Ac)2 to evaluate its application in real condition. The schematic diagram of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP based Zn-air battery was presented in Fig. 8 a and Figure S25. Another Zn-air battery was also set up using 20 % Pt/C catalyst as the air cathode for comparison (the mass loading was 1.0 mg cm−2). The charge-discharge polarization curve of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP suggest that it possesses remarkable ORR and OER bifunctional catalytic performances in Figure S26. Besides, as can be seen in Fig. 8b, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP based Zn-air battery displayed a higher peak power density (97 mW cm−2) than that of 20 % Pt/C (78 mW cm−2). The specific capacity of Co/Fe-TPDA-CP based Zn-air battery was 780 mA h g −1 also advanced than 20 % Pt/C catalyst (642 mA h g −1) under the condition of normalizing the mass of consumed zinc in Fig. 8c. Especially, a long-term discharge-charge test was practiced to disclose its stability and reversibility at 10 mA cm−2, as displayed in Fig. 8d-g, Co/Fe-TPDA-CP based Zn-air battery demonstrate a high round-trip efficiency of 52.61% and a small charge/discharge voltage gap of 0.98 V with the charge potential of 2.05 V, discharge potential of 1.07 V. After 60,000 s cycling (450 cycles of charge-discharge cycles) operation, the charge-discharge voltage gap only increased to 1.01 V and round-trip efficiency only decreased to 51.47% in the Fig. 8e-g. While the Pt/C based battery exhibit an initial charge potential of 2.04 V, discharge potential of 1.27 V. After only 7000 s cycling, it performs a rapid degradation with the potential gap expands from 0.77 to 1.41 V, indicating Co/Fe-TPDA-CP based Zn-air battery possess long-term durability than that of Pt/C. The above results confirm that Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is a promising bifunction oxygen electrocatalyst that can be used as a cathode in Zn-air batteries. 4 Conclusions In summary, for the first time, the aromatic amine derivative N,N,N',N'-Tetra(4-aldehydephenyl)−1,4-phenylenediamine was used as a linker with functional cobalt tetra-aminophthalocyanine and iron tetra-aminophthalocyanine to prepare a molecular catalyst with Fe-N4 and Co-N4 bimetallic active sites. The as-prepared Co/Fe-TPDA-CP catalyst exhibited excellent ORR and OER performance. The synergistic effect of the bimetallic sites was illustrated by energy band structure, kinetic analysis and free energy thermodynamic analysis. Firstly, the introduction of the second metal dramatically changes the molecular energy band structure. Co/Fe-TPDA-CP has a high HOMO and higher electron donation ability, which improves the oxygen-electrical activity of the catalyst to some extent. In addition, the adsorption energy between the reaction intermediate and the active site was optimized by the changing of d-band center, which led to the optimal RDS of the ORR/OER process. Kinetic and thermodynamic analyses indicate that Fe-N4 is the main active site for direct 4-electron transfer, whereas Co-N4 accelerates the continuous 2-electron transfer process in Fe-N4 that promotes partial decomposition of H2O2. The synergistic effects of the bimetallic sites promoted the decomposition of a portion of the hydrogen peroxide to obtain high activity and stability, which was further demonstrated in a practical zinc-air battery. This study lays the foundation for the precise adjustment of the electronic structure of the active center at the molecular level and on the design of macrocyclic polymer catalysts. coredata.dc:description: Bifunctional catalysts for oxygen reduction reaction and oxygen evolution reaction in Zinc-air batteries have been long pursued for the development of clean energy transformation devices. Yet, the underlying mechanism of the promoted electrocatalytic performance is still vague. Herein, a pyrolysis-free Co/Fe bimetallic phthalocyanine coordination polymer Co/Fe-TPDA-CP is firstly synthesized using heterometal tetra-aminophthalocyanines (MTAPcs, M=Co/Fe) as structural model and N,N,N’,N’-tetra(4-folmylphenyl)-p-phenylenediamine (TPDA) as linker. The Co/Fe-TPDA-CP exhibits the high oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) and oxygen evolution reaction (OER) activities with low ΔE of 692 mV, superior to monometallic Fe-TPDA-CP and Co-TPDA-CP polymers. Density functional theory (DFT) calculation and thermodynamic analysis find that ORR and OER happened separately on Fe and Co sites, in which the presence of second metal modulates the d-band center and optimizes the intermediates adsorption, thereby improving the ORR/OER synergistically. Moreover, dynamic analysis explains that the enhanced ORR stability originated from the fast H2O2 decomposition catalyzed by Co-N4 sites. Furthermore, the Zn-air battery with Co/Fe-TPDA-CP electrode also exhibits a high peak power density (97 mW cm−2) and specific capacity (780 mA h g −1). Through the proof-of-concept bifunctional electrocatalyst with clear structure and synergistic mechanism, this work paves the way for future molecular oxygen electrocatalyst design.
